In TypeScript, you can use type guards to tell the type system that you know a value will only have a specific type, even though it could theoretically have multiple types. Type guards are a way to narrow down the type of a variable, and they can be implemented using various techniques such as type assertions, custom type predicates, or specific type-checking functions.

Here are a few common ways to achieve this:

### 1. Type Assertions
Type assertions can be used to tell TypeScript that you know the type of a value at runtime, even if it could be other types at compile time.

```typescript
let value: any = "hello";

if (typeof value === 'string') {
  value = value; // Type assertion
  console.log(value.length); // No error
} else {
  value = value; // Type assertion
  console.log(value.toFixed()); // No error
}
```

### 2. Custom Type Predicates
You can create a custom type predicate function to narrow down the type of a variable.

```typescript
function isString(value: any): value is string {
  return typeof value === 'string';
}

let value: any = "hello";

if (isString(value)) {
  value = value; // Now TypeScript knows `value` is a string
  console.log(value.length); // No error
} else {
  value = value; // Now TypeScript knows `value` is a number
  console.log(value.toFixed()); // No error
}
```

### 3. Discriminated Unions
If you have a union type and one of the types has a discriminant property, you can use that property to narrow down the type.

```typescript
interface Animal {
  type: 'animal';
  name: string;
}

interface Bird {
  type: 'bird';
  name: string;
  canFly: boolean;
}

let value: Animal | Bird = { type: 'bird', name: 'sparrow', canFly: true };

if (value.type === 'bird') {
  value = value; // TypeScript knows `value` is a Bird
  console.log(value.canFly); // No error
} else {
  value = value; // TypeScript knows `value` is an Animal
  console.log(value.name); // No error
}
```

### 4. Type Guards with `instanceof`
If you are working with classes, you can use `instanceof` to narrow down the type.

```typescript
class Animal {}
class Bird extends Animal {
  canFly: boolean;
}

let value: Animal | Bird = new Bird();

if (value instanceof Bird) {
  value = value; // TypeScript knows `value` is a Bird
  console.log(value.canFly); // No error
} else {
  value = value; // TypeScript knows `value` is an Animal
  console.log(value instanceof Animal); // No error
}
```

By using these techniques, you can tell TypeScript that you know the type of a value will be more specific than what it could theoretically be, which helps the type system provide better type checking and error messages.

